## 8. Documentation Governance

Canonical docs live in a numbered tree:

```
docs/
├── 1_Blueprints/        # System design documents
├── 2_User_Guides/       # Feature-based user documentation
├── 3_Developer_Docs/    # API reference, data dictionary, settings reference
└── _archive/            # Historical reports and audits — read-only
```

Rules:

- **No report files in the repository root.** Analyses and audits go to
  `docs/_archive/` or nowhere.
- **`CHANGELOG.md` is always required** — every release updates it, no
  exceptions. The documentation stage blocks the PR otherwise.
- Docs are feature-based, not report-based: update the guide for the feature
  you changed rather than writing a new document about the change.

**Doc-update map** — when you change X, update Y:

| Change area | Doc file to update |
| :--- | :--- |
| <!-- e.g. Payments module --> | <!-- docs/2_User_Guides/... --> |
| API changes | <!-- docs/3_Developer_Docs/API_Reference.md --> |
| Database schema | <!-- docs/3_Developer_Docs/Data_Dictionary.md --> |
| Any change | `CHANGELOG.md` (always) |

## 9. Versioning

Semantic versioning, tracked in a `VERSION` file at the repo root, with a
[Keep a Changelog](https://keepachangelog.com/)-style `CHANGELOG.md`.

| Change | Bump |
| :--- | :--- |
| Breaking change, schema migration with data impact | MAJOR |
| New feature, new module | MINOR |
| Bug fix, small improvement | PATCH |

**On release:**

1. Update the `VERSION` file (done at Checkpoint D, with the approved version).
2. Update `CHANGELOG.md` under a `vX.Y.Z` heading matching `VERSION` exactly.
3. After the PR merges: `git tag -a vX.Y.Z -m "Release vX.Y.Z"` and push the
   tag. Tags are created only after merge, never on feature branches.

